“boat.” (See Meile, “Les Yavanas dans I'Inde tamoule,” pp. 90-92.) The Chinese used an expression K’un-lun-tan, which could be an equivalent of the Greek kolandia (information from R. Stein). For his part, Anthony H. Christie, “The Name K'un-lun as an Ethnic Term,” Proceedings, XXllle Congrès International des Orientalistes (Cambridge, 1954), p. 29, explains the expression kolandiaphonta megista (Periplus, $60) as a distortion of kolandiapha onta (ta) megista, and considers kolandiapha as a Gteek transcription of the Chinese k’un-lunpo, the character representing the name for “boat” in various dialects of Southeast Asia. This thesis is developed in Christie's “An Obscure Passage from the Periplus,” BSOAS, XIX (1957), pp. 345-53.

