As far as architecture is concerned, we have at Phra Pathom the lower part of a Buddhist monument resting on a double substructure with steps: on each face, five images of the seated Buddha are placed in niches flanked by colonnettes and pilasters. Other substructures, perhaps older, have been found farther west, at Phong Tuk on the Kanburi River, associated with a bronze lamp of Hellenistic origin and with statuettes of the Buddha in post-Gupta style. See Pierre Dupont, L’Archéologie méne de Dvaravati (Paris, 1959).

